The surface functional groups of CDs were analyzed by Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FTIR). As shown in 
                           Fig. S4
                        , the absorption peak at 3270 cm−1 was due to the O-H stretching vibration, while 2948 cm−1 and 2872 cm−1 were caused by the saturated C-H stretching vibration. The absorption peak at 1560 cm−1 was responded to the stretching vibration of C = O from –COOH groups, whereas 1390 cm−1 was caused by C-N telescopic vibration. The absorption peak at 1061 cm−1 was due to the C-O stretching vibration, while the absorption peak at 880 cm−1 was attributed to the bending vibration of N-H from –NH2 groups. The full scan X-ray Photoelectron Spectroscopy (XPS) showed that CDs were mainly composed of C (83.5 %), N (10.7 %) and O (3.8 %) (
                           Fig. S5
                        ). Furthermore, the high-resolution C spectrum (
                           Fig. S6
                        ) showed the presence of four different types of C: C-C/C = C (284.70 eV), C-N (285.23 eV), C = N (286.16 eV), and C = O (287.81 eV) [47]. The high-resolution N spectrum (
                           Fig. S7
                        ) showed three peaks at 398.29 eV, 399.81 eV, and 400.93 eV, which were corresponded to pyridine nitrogen, pyrrole nitrogen, and graphitic nitrogen, respectively [48,49]. The high-resolution O spectrum (
                           Fig. S8
                        ) showed two different types of O: C-O (531.92 eV) and C = O (532.95 eV). The results from FTIR and XPS indicated that the surfaces of CDs contained a certain amount of hydroxyl, carboxyl groups and amino groups.

The pore features of both wood and CDs-Wood were further investigated with the BET test by physical adsorption of N2 at a temperature of 77 K. The adsorption isotherms of both materials are following type II curves (
                           Fig. S11
                        ). At high pressures (P/P0 > 0.9), significant nitrogen absorption was observed in CDs-Wood, demonstrating the existence of numerous large pores. The pore size distribution was determined using density functional theory (DFT), Barret-Joyner-Halenda (BJH), and Horvath-Kawazoe (HK) models, respectively. The CDs-Wood had micropores of approximately 1.19 nm, whereas the micropores of wood were around 0.53 nm (
                           Fig. S12
                        ). This indicated that the hydrothermal process resulted in the enlargement of the micropores, owing to the degradation of lignin. There are hardly any changes in the mesopores and macropores of CDs-Wood, as compared to the raw wood (
                           Fig. S13, S14
                        ).
